levitate.example3: Celia maintains that no amount of money is worth such an excruciating experience, but Hector is insistent, and so they continue to travel, levitating tables and producing phantom knocking on all manner of well-papered walls.

skittle.example1: John Tookey showed off this new New York craze called break dancing but went spinning out of control into a group of girls, who toppled like skittles.
skittle.example2: Walls of villagers skittled over, down, around, over.
skittle.example3: Bowling his body into a forward roll, he knocked Matthias down like a skittle.

unhook.example1: Oliver unhooked the bag from the doorknob and left the bag of cookies in front of the door.
unhook.example2: She slid out of the stump and unhooked the bow and quiver from her pack.
unhook.example3: Seeing our state, the old man walked over to a well, unhooked a tin pail, and dropped it carefully down into the water.

looting.definition: To steal, especially as part of war, riot or other group violence.
looting.example1: His voice, made metallic by the amplifiers, boomed forth an endless catalogue of atrocities, massacres, deportations, lootings, rapings, torture of prison-ers, bombing of civilians, lying propaganda, unjust aggressions, broken treaties.
looting.example2: “The news coming out of the city, it’s so bad. There’s looting, killing. Something bad is going to happen to you.”
looting.example3: There didn’t seem to be any logic to taking a man brought in for gasoline-siphoning and placing him with four men suspected of working together on crimes varying from looting to terrorism.

goatee.example1: Only the face with its reddish moustache and goatee was left exposed.
goatee.example2: He was a small dignified scholar with a white goatee beard, and as far as I could gather, he was an astrologer, a meteorologist and a speaker of ancient Greek.
goatee.example3: The flat-faced man went ahead of them and the man with the goatee brought up the rear, shotgun at the ready.

manatee.example1: The three American manatees were still hanging out in the middle of the room.
manatee.example2: “Yeah, manatees. If you have a water hose, they come right up and drink from it. They have whiskers and a nose like an elephant whose trunk didn’t fully grow.”
manatee.example3: “This is where the manatees come in the winter, right?”

imagined.definition: To form a mental image of something; to envision or create something in one's mind.
imagined.example1: I think about that, and the way he used to be—the way they used to be, the way I imagined them to be—and I feel bereft.
imagined.example2: She did not want him to stop, but she had imagined this differently, assumed they would make a carefully planned ceremony of it.
imagined.example3: He had not imagined that a woman would dare to speak so to a man.

seven.definition: The digit/figure 7 or an occurrence thereof.
seven.example1: One summer weekend, when I was around seven years old, I was at a public swimming pool with the whole family.
seven.example2: That was a bornb that went off in the middle of a big train station in London the day after Aunt Penn went to Oslo and something like seven or seventy thousand people got killed.
seven.example3: Mom explained that she had pulmonary fibrosis, and it was getting worse, but I was seven years old, and pulmonary fibrosis were two big, grown-up words I didn’t understand.

telltale.example1: While Dad read, I monitored the telltale vein in the top left corner of his forehead.
telltale.example2: Actually, only a trace is enough to incorporate the telltale musty odor and taste.
telltale.example3: Once in Tarbean I saw a young girl of no more than sixteen with the telltale hollow eyes and unnaturally white teeth of the hopelessly addicted.

rowing.definition: To propel (a boat or other craft) over water using oars.
rowing.example1: After three hours of rowing like galley slaves, distance had shrunk the island to the size of an open hand.
rowing.example2: When we were away from the bank and someone else was rowing and there was nothing more for me to do, I bent over with my head on my knees, my heart in pieces.
rowing.example3: I was recovering from everything but embarrassment, and Grandma was rowing out from the bank.

quickie.example1: Then he went to Reno, Nevada, and got himself a quickie divorce.
quickie.example2: He did not see the task as a ticket to fame, so he designed what he called a “quickie experiment” involving a single neutron detector placed in a stairway outside the cyclotron room.
quickie.example3: Honestly, though, there are not a lot of options around here, and I’m guessing he’s not making a mad break for Vegas for a quickie wedding.

conducting.definition: To lead, or guide; to escort.
conducting.example1: Their crime was conducting unthinkable research on Jews without consent—sewing siblings together to create Siamese twins, dissecting people alive to study organ function.
conducting.example2: Classes were canceled and the masters spent several hours of each day conducting examinations.
conducting.example3: When they see a police car coming or that officers are conducting a sweep, they unlatch their front gates and usher migrants in to hide in their gardens and backyards.

attentively.example1: We listened attentively to see if he was going to embellish the story with more striking details.
attentively.example2: In any event, his mother comparatively soon wanted to visit Gregor, but his father and his sister restrained her, at first with reasons which Gregor listened to very attentively and which he completely endorsed.
attentively.example3: The dogs were arrayed in a half circle around them, watching attentively.

readership.definition: The collected readers of a publication.
readership.example1: To a readership obliged to watch in disbelief as the legions toppled one Greek-speaking kingdom after the other, Polybius begged to offer some historical context.
readership.example2: Foreign papers reflected the outrage of their readership.
readership.example3: He concurred that such lively observations about homestead life would be of general interest to his readership.

zenith.definition: The point in the sky vertically above a given position or observer; the point in the celestial sphere opposite the nadir.
zenith.example1: As the sun approached its zenith, and the park bustled with midday traffic, the heat transformed the hidey-hole into a wretched furnace.
zenith.example2: That idea escalates to its macabre zenith in Nazi Germany in the 1940s, where human eugenics is used to justify grotesque experiments, culminating in confinement, sterilization, euthanasia, and mass murder.
zenith.example3: Now, there are 60 minutes of arc in an angular degree, and 90 degrees, a right angle, from the horizon to the zenith.

soreness.example1: Nathan willed himself forward against the soreness in his feet and the stiffness in his knees.
soreness.example2: She was terribly stiff from rowing and sleeping in the damp, but as she paddled, the soreness went away.
soreness.example3: The pain and the pounding inside his head were gone, but when he sat up he had to move slowly to avoid jarring the soreness inside his skull.

stator.definition: The stationary part of a motor or other machine.
stator.example1: A molecular rotor consists of a central rotating molecule that is connected by axis molecules to stationary stator molecules, similar to the way that a wheel and axle are connected to a car frame.
stator.example2: The main part of the T is one of the windings on the rotor while the line above it, separated by a space, is the stator.
stator.example3: The magnetic force of the rotor magnets and the gap between the coreless stator and rotor magnets has also been tweaked, giving SL-1200MK7 torque that the company says is on par with the SL-1200MK5.

exoplanet.example1: As these so-called exoplanets were being discovered, scientists began to develop instruments to analyse the chemical composition of their atmospheres.
exoplanet.example2: While many exoplanets are Venus-like, the study suggests that astronomers should narrow their focus to exoplanets which are more like Earth.
exoplanet.example3: "Studying connections between different atmospheric layers is very important for all planets, whether it's an exoplanet, Jupiter or Earth," Wong said.

contiguous.example1: The only building in sight was a small block of yellow brick sitting on the edge of the waste land, a sort of compact Main Street ministering to it and contiguous to absolutely nothing.
contiguous.example2: Quite a few of those families occupy large contiguous areas—in the case of Indo-European, the area encompassing most of Europe east through much of western Asia to India.
contiguous.example3: In the case of where herons live, most readers know that the northern United States is contiguous to Canada and that the two have similar ecosystems, so they don’t need a similarly.

maximal.definition: The element of a set with the greatest magnitude.
maximal.example1: The problem, you realize, is that while you have been raised to speak quietly and little, the notions of where you come from and who you are need a maximal approach.
maximal.example2: This piece has the hallmarks of López Bellido’s style, such as rich orchestration and maximal gesture, along with homages to the folk songs and rhythms of the Black Peruvian music that the title hints at.
maximal.example3: Davis’s arrangements include elements of progressive rock—his work is dramatic, maximal, ambitious—and of New Age music, which, in the mid-seventies, was just beginning to find its center as a genre.

expressed.definition: To convey or communicate; to make known or explicit.
expressed.example1: My companion expressed no surprise at this emotion, nor did he question me as to its cause; he only said—
expressed.example2: The need to make music, and to listen to it, is universally expressed by human beings.
expressed.example3: She asked Joyce how her parents were doing, and expressed her regret when Joyce replied that her father was quite ill.

tripping.example1: Through Cavern Hole he clattered in the darkness, stumbling and tripping over furniture, his heart hammering loudly and legs pumping like twin pistons.
tripping.example2: Kim had a swollen eye and a bad scrape on her thigh as a result of her tripping over her backpack as she attempted to kick me.
tripping.example3: I will admit that twice I feigned tripping on a rock just so my right arm would brush against her breast, and that was awesome.

penitentiary.example1: But here’s what happened, as near as I can tell: When I got to the corner, Doug Swieteck’s brother and the state penitentiary crowd were waiting for me on the other side.
penitentiary.example2: It’s bad enough that the great city of San Francisco should suffer the indignity of a maximum security federal penitentiary in its midst without being subject to these sorts of sick and dangerous shenanigans.
penitentiary.example3: “They were telling the reporter Shotgun killed a man and went to the penitentiary. ”
